**HTML, CSS, JavaScript**: Basics of structuring and styling web pages. - **Responsive Design**: Techniques to make web applications work on different devices (desktop, tablet, mobile). ### 2. **Frontend Development** - **JavaScript Frameworks**: Learn React.js, Angular, or Vue.js to build interactive and responsive user interfaces. - **State Management**: Understanding Redux or Vuex for managing the application's state. - **UI/UX Design**: Basics of designing user interfaces using Material UI, Bootstrap, or Tailwind CSS. - **Data Visualization**: Using libraries like D3.js, Chart.js, or Highcharts for creating charts and graphs. ### 3. **Backend Development** - **Programming Languages**: Learn Node.js with Express.js, Python with Django or Flask, or Java with Spring Boot for server-side development. - **Database Management**: - **SQL**: Learn relational databases like PostgreSQL or MySQL for structured data. - **NoSQL**: Understand NoSQL databases like MongoDB or Elasticsearch for unstructured data. - **APIs**: Learn to develop and consume RESTful or GraphQL APIs. - **Authentication and Authorization**: Concepts like OAuth 2.0, JWT, and LDAP for secure user management. ### 4. **Data Integration and Processing** - **ETL Tools**: Basics of ETL (Extract, Transform, Load) processes with tools like Apache NiFi or Talend. - **Data Processing**: Libraries like Pandas (Python) or Apache Spark for analyzing and processing large datasets. ### 5. **Collaboration Tools** - **Real-time Communication**: WebSockets (e.g., Socket.io) for real-time updates and collaborative editing. - **Version Control**: Git-based systems or custom versioning mechanisms to track changes and manage document integrity. ### 6. **DevOps and Deployment** - **Containerization**: Understanding Docker for packaging applications and Kubernetes for orchestration. - **CI/CD Pipelines**: Tools like Jenkins, GitHub Actions, or GitLab CI for automating testing and deployment. - **Cloud Services**: Basics of cloud platforms like AWS, Azure, or Google Cloud for hosting and scaling applications. ### 7. **Security** - **Encryption**: Techniques like SSL/TLS for securing data in transit and AES for data at rest. - **Compliance**: Understanding regulations like GDPR, FERPA, and how to implement them in your application. ### 8. **Internationalization (i18n)** - **Multilingual Support**: Libraries like i18next or React Intl for supporting multiple languages in your application. ### 9. **Agile Development** - **Scrum/Kanban**: Methodologies to manage project development efficiently. - **Testing Strategies**: Unit tests, integration tests, and user acceptance testing (UAT). ### 10. **Monitoring and Maintenance** - **Monitoring Tools**: Prometheus, Grafana for performance monitoring, and ELK Stack for logging. - **Analytics**: Tools like Google Analytics or New Relic for tracking user engagement and system performance. Learning these concepts will give you a solid foundation to build and maintain the proposed web-based portal. google meet? ? ? ? / ? ? ? ? ? ? ? / ? ? /"/ ? ? yo woa woa chill can't come call rn text here When come call? too much noise here Ok 1min okk do git pull Ok yess npm i and then go to src folder +page is the main page don't mess with file names, it won't work go to components folder that's what I've made Ok Bro for me when it is showing error in +page ignore go to terminal npm run dev what do you see i see what u made did u learn svelte ? yes sort of send me the link where u learned svelte i will get basic idea on it and then help u with css nvm ### Project Summary: Attendance Tracking Mobile Application for GAIL (INDIA) LTD **Objective:** The goal is to develop a mobile application that automates and streamlines the attendance tracking process for employees across multiple office locations. The app will utilize geolocation technology to ensure accurate and efficient recording of check-in and check-out times, aiming to enhance operational efficiency, reduce manual errors, and provide a user-friendly experience for employees. **Key Requirements:** 1. **Geolocation-Based Check-In and Check-Out:** - **Automatic Recording:** The app will automatically record the check-in time and geo-location when an employee enters within a 200-meter radius of their office. Similarly, it will automatically record the check-out time when the employee exits the 200-meter radius. - **Consistency:** Each check-in must have a corresponding check-out, even if an employee enters and leaves the office multiple times in a day. 2. **Manual Location Check-In / Check-Out for Offsite Work:** - **Offsite Feature:** The app will provide a manual check-in and check-out option for employees working at locations other than their designated offices. - **Location Suggestions:** The app will automatically suggest relevant locations based on the employee’s real-time longitude and latitude, allowing them to confirm their check-in or check-out at these suggested locations. 3. **Working Hours Calculation:** - The app will calculate the total working hours of employees based on the recorded check-in and check-out data. 4. **Data Accuracy and Integrity:** - **Real-Time Synchronization:** The app will ensure real-time data synchronization to prevent data loss and maintain accurate records. - **Secure Storage:** All data will be securely stored to ensure its integrity and protect it from tampering. **Constraints:** - **Resource Limitations:** GAIL (INDIA) LTD will not provide any hardware, software, licenses, data, or other resources. The development team must rely entirely on free and/or open-source resources for the project. **Link to Problem Statement Video:** This project focuses on creating a robust and efficient solution that leverages modern technology to address the challenges of manual attendance tracking while ensuring data reliability and security. Yoo Rohan suggested that we can try hardware Development of a suction based low-cost flush (with less water usage) for deployment in rural areas.? 1643 The proposed solution is a comprehensive portal aimed at tracking, measuring, and showcasing innovation excellence in educational institutions. It will integrate data from various sources (research projects, grants, publications, patents, competitions, etc.), allowing for detailed analysis and visualization of innovation indicators. The system will be user-friendly, secure, and compliant with educational standards, providing customizable dashboards for different user roles (faculty, students, administrators), mechanisms for recognizing achievements, and collaboration features. Key Features: User Authentication and Role Management: Secure login for different user roles (e.g., administrators, faculty, students). Role-based access to ensure privacy. Data Collection and Integration: Import data from multiple sources (research management systems, project databases). Manual data entry support. Innovation Indicators: Define and track innovation metrics like publications, patents, awards, etc. Customizable indicators per department. Data Analysis and Visualization: Tools for trend analysis. Customizable dashboards with graphs and charts. Recognition and Incentives: Highlight top performers and generate reports or certificates. Collaboration and Feedback: Collaborative data entry and review. Feedback collection and version control. User Experience: Intuitive, responsive design with multilingual support. Compliance: Adherence to educational and reporting standards (GDPR, FERPA). Technologies Needed: Front-End: React.js or Angular: For building a dynamic and interactive user interface. Bootstrap or Material UI: For creating responsive designs. Back-End: Node.js (Express) or Django (Python): For API and server-side logic. Flask: As a lightweight alternative for smaller applications. Database: PostgreSQL or MySQL: For storing research, publication, and user data. MongoDB: For more flexible storage needs. Data Analysis and Visualization: D3.js, Chart.js, or Highcharts: For creating interactive charts and graphs. Pandas, NumPy (Python): For data manipulation and analysis. Authentication and Security: OAuth 2.0, JWT: For secure user authentication and session management. SSL/TLS: For encrypted data transmission. Collaboration Tools: Socket.io: For real-time collaboration features. Git for version control. Data Import/Export: Pandas (Python): For handling data import/export from Excel, CSV files. OpenPyXL or XlsxWriter: For generating reports in Excel format. Cloud Infrastructure: AWS or Google Cloud: For hosting and scalable storage. Kubernetes and Docker: For containerization and deployment. Compliance: GDPR and FERPA tools: For managing privacy and data protection regulations. This stack will ensure the portal is scalable, secure, and adaptable to different institutional needs. Gujarat, recognized for its innovation and entrepreneurship ecosystem, is facing challenges in the management and monitoring of research activities, intellectual property rights (IPR), innovation developments, and start-up growth. Current systems are fragmented, with information scattered across different departments, creating inefficiencies in data accessibility, resource allocation, and overall project management. To address these issues, a comprehensive web application is proposed. Key Features: Unified Data Repository: Centralized storage of research projects, patents, innovations, and start-up data to improve accessibility. Transparent Monitoring: Tools for stakeholders to track the progress and outcomes of research, innovation, and start-ups, ensuring transparency. Efficient Resource Allocation: Mechanisms for real-time optimization of resources like funding and mentorship, driven by data insights. IPR Management: Streamlined processes for patent applications, tracking, and intellectual property protection. Support for Innovators and Start-ups: Access to mentorship, resources, and services to help entrepreneurs grow. Collaboration Tools: Enhanced collaboration among researchers, policy makers, and investors, fostering a unified innovation ecosystem. Data-Driven Insights: Analytics and reporting features to provide stakeholders with actionable insights for decision-making. Target Users: Researchers/Academics: Need a platform to manage research projects, collaborations, and funding. Innovators/Entrepreneurs: Require centralized resources and support for innovation and start-up growth. Policy Makers/Government: Benefit from data-driven insights for informed policy formulation and resource distribution. Investors/Funding Agencies: Need transparency in evaluating research and start-ups for investment. IPR Professionals: Require efficient tools for managing and protecting intellectual property rights. Expected Outcomes: Centralized Data Repository: Reduces data fragmentation and improves accessibility. Increased Transparency: Better tracking of research, innovation, and start-up progress. Improved Resource Utilization: More effective allocation of resources to drive better research and innovation outcomes. Accelerated Innovation: Faster innovation cycles due to better support and collaboration systems. Economic Growth: Higher success rates for start-ups and innovations, contributing to Gujarat's economic development. Enhanced IPR Protection: Improved efficiency in managing and safeguarding intellectual property. In summary, this comprehensive web application aims to streamline processes, enhance collaboration, and provide tools to drive innovation and economic growth in Gujarat, creating a cohesive and efficient environment for research, entrepreneurship, and intellectual property management. 1608 Use of Digital Knowledge Sharing Platform like Wikis on sharing of water efficient techniques and methods for minimizing water scarcity. 1690\ woahh do you have any clue on how we go about any hardware stuff let's do it tho interesting bro no one of us has any idea in hardware look i am not against it or smtg it is intresting and new stuff we can learn but we got less than seven days to submit an solution and if you really, i mean really want to get selected let us do smtg we actually know about what statements i sent u now has 0-3 submissions we can try this cause we have a basic idea once see the problem statements i sent and if you like anything we will do it and submit we have to do this quick cause we shld give it to that choss guy for registration so need to do it way before 20 and our GAIL project has 9 submissions I mean 10 it got updated just now ohhh 50% chance yep I think more might come broo our thing is like kinda doable for beginners like us yea ik we shld apply for second one is it in bangalore? We got a lot to study I didn't touch biology ,git roshani will handle it we just chill Ok We will do it Somehow we will manage yahh thanks bro sticker omitted image omitted Part A: Short Answers 1. Define Biochemistry. Biochemistry is the branch of science that explores the chemical processes within and related to living organisms. 2. Define Biomimetics. Biomimetics is the study of biological structures and functions to inspire the design of materials and systems that mimic nature. 3. Differences between plant and animal cells. Plant cells have a cell wall, chloroplasts, and large vacuoles, while animal cells do not. Animal cells have lysosomes and centrioles, which plant cells typically lack. 4. Differences between prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells. Prokaryotic cells lack a nucleus and membrane-bound organelles, while eukaryotic cells have a nucleus and well-defined organelles. 5. Functions of proteins. Proteins serve various functions, including structural support (e.g., collagen), enzymes (e.g., catalase), transport (e.g., hemoglobin), and immune response (e.g., antibodies). 6. Functions of carbohydrates. Carbohydrates provide energy (glucose), store energy (glycogen, starch), and serve structural roles (cellulose in plants). 7. Name any 2 bioplastics. Polyhydroxyalkanoates (PHA) and Polylactic Acid (PLA). 8. Name the 2 different types of nucleic acids. DNA (Deoxyribonucleic Acid) and RNA (Ribonucleic Acid). 9. How are carbohydrates classified? Carbohydrates are classified into monosaccharides (e.g., glucose), disaccharides (e.g., sucrose), and polysaccharides (e.g., starch, cellulose). 10. What are the building blocks of proteins? Amino acids. 11. Name the storage plant polysaccharide. Starch. 12. Name the component of blood used for the transport of oxygen. Hemoglobin. 13. Name the process used to convert organic waste into biogas, a renewable form of energy. Anaerobic digestion. 14. Properties of enzymes. Enzymes are biological catalysts, specific to substrates, function best at optimal pH and temperature, and can be reused. --- Part B: Long Answers 1. Blood pressure, systolic and diastolic pressure. Blood pressure is the force exerted by circulating blood on the walls of blood vessels. It is measured in two numbers: Systolic pressure: The pressure in the arteries when the heart beats (normal range: 90-120 mm Hg). Diastolic pressure: The pressure in the arteries when the heart rests between beats (normal range: 60-80 mm Hg). High blood pressure (hypertension) can lead to cardiovascular diseases, while low blood pressure (hypotension) can cause dizziness and fainting. 2. Reasons for hypotension and preventive measures. Hypotension can occur due to dehydration, heart problems, endocrine issues, severe infection, or blood loss. Preventive measures include staying hydrated, eating a balanced diet, and avoiding sudden changes in posture. Regular monitoring and treatment of underlying conditions are also important. 3. Major differences between animal and plant cells with neat labeled diagrams. Plant cells: Have a rigid cell wall made of cellulose, large central vacuoles for storage, and chloroplasts for photosynthesis. Animal cells: Lack a cell wall and chloroplasts but have small vacuoles, lysosomes, and centrioles for cell division. Diagram: You can refer to typical textbook illustrations showing organelles like the nucleus, mitochondria, and other structures specific to each cell type. 4. Significance of nucleic acids, their role in the vaccine industry, and DNA fingerprinting. Nucleic acids (DNA and RNA) store and transmit genetic information. DNA carries the instructions for organism development, and RNA plays a crucial role in protein synthesis. In the vaccine industry, nucleic acids are essential in the development of mRNA vaccines (e.g., COVID-19 vaccines). These vaccines use RNA to instruct cells to produce proteins that trigger immune responses. DNA fingerprinting is a forensic technique used to identify individuals by analyzing unique sequences in their DNA, used in criminal investigations and paternity tests. 5. Structure and functions of the heart. The heart is a muscular organ with four chambers: two atria and two ventricles. It pumps oxygenated blood from the lungs to the body and returns deoxygenated blood back to the lungs. Key structures include the atria (receiving chambers), ventricles (pumping chambers), valves (prevent backflow of blood), and the aorta (main artery). The heart's electrical system regulates its rhythm, ensuring continuous blood flow through pulmonary and systemic circulation. 6. Role of water in homeostasis and its role as a significant biomolecule. Water is essential for maintaining homeostasis by regulating body temperature, facilitating chemical reactions, and transporting nutrients and waste. As a solvent, water allows biochemical reactions to occur in the body. It also helps maintain fluid balance and supports cellular structure. 7. Comment on the scope of biology for engineers. Biology offers engineers insights into biomedicine, bioinformatics, and biotechnology. Biomedical engineers develop medical devices, while biotechnologists work on genetic engineering and sustainable technologies such as biofuels. Engineers can also develop biomimetic materials by studying biological systems. 8. Explain echolocation. Some of its uses in navigation. Echolocation is the biological process used by animals like bats and dolphins to detect objects by emitting sound waves and listening to their echoes. It is used for navigation, hunting, and avoiding obstacles in low visibility environments. In human applications, echolocation has inspired sonar and radar technologies used in submarines and aircraft. 9. Compare the design of aircraft to birds. Aircraft designs are inspired by the streamlined shape and aerodynamic features of birds, such as wings for lift and tail structures for stability and control. Birds use feathers and muscle coordination for flight, while aircraft use engines and flaps to manipulate airflow and generate thrust. 10. Define metabolism. Differences between anabolism and catabolism. Metabolism encompasses all chemical reactions in an organism that maintain life. It consists of two main processes: Anabolism: The constructive part, where small molecules combine to form larger molecules (e.g., protein synthesis). Catabolism: The breakdown of large molecules into smaller ones, releasing energy (e.g., cellular respiration). 11. Explain photosynthesis as bioenergy. Photosynthesis is the process by which green plants and some organisms convert light energy into chemical energy stored in glucose. This process takes place in chloroplasts using sunlight, water, and carbon dioxide. As a bioenergy source, it forms the base of most food chains and has the potential to be harnessed for renewable energy. 12. Differences between prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells. Prokaryotic cells: Simple, lack a defined nucleus and organelles, DNA is circular, and they reproduce via binary fission (e.g., bacteria). Eukaryotic cells: Complex, have a defined nucleus, membrane-bound organelles, and linear DNA (e.g., plants, animals, fungi). 13. Comment on proteins with respect to structure, functions, and applications. Structure: Proteins are made of long chains of amino acids folded into complex three-dimensional shapes. There are four levels of protein structure: primary, secondary, tertiary, and quaternary. Functions: They serve as enzymes, hormones, structural components (collagen), and transport molecules (hemoglobin). Applications: Proteins are used in biotechnology (enzymes for industrial processes), medicine (insulin, vaccines), and food science (casein in milk). Part A: Short Answers 1. Define Biochemistry. Landing Page Description: The landing page welcomes users and provides an overview of the website's purpose: to recommend personalized job opportunities based on user profiles and preferences. Actions: Sign Up / Log In: Users can create an account or log in to access personalized features. Explore Jobs: A button to explore popular job listings without an account. 2. User Registration / Login Description: Users can register by providing their email, creating a password, and filling in basic information. Actions: Input Fields: Email, Password, Name, and optional fields like LinkedIn profile or resume upload. Verification: A verification email is sent upon registration to confirm the account. 3. User Profile Setup Description: After logging in, users are prompted to complete their profile for tailored job recommendations. Actions: Job Preferences: Select preferred job titles, industries, and locations. Skills Assessment: Users can list their skills or take a short assessment to identify strengths. Experience Level: Indicate years of experience and current job status (e.g., unemployed, looking for a change). 4. Job Recommendations Dashboard Description: This is the main interface where users receive personalized job recommendations. Features: Recommended Jobs: A list of jobs tailored to the user based on their profile, displayed with job title, company, location, and brief description. Filters: Options to filter by job type (full-time, part-time, remote) and industry. Save/Apply Buttons: Users can save jobs for later or apply directly through the site. 5. Machine Learning Model Insights Description: Users can see how the ML model generates recommendations. Actions: "Why This Job?" Feature: Click on a job to see why it was recommended, such as matching skills, experience, or preferences. Feedback Loop: Users can provide feedback on the recommendations (e.g., "Not interested" or "Great match") to improve future suggestions. 6. Job Application Process Description: Streamlined application process for recommended jobs. Actions: Direct Application: Users can apply through the site, filling in necessary details and uploading their resume. Application Tracking: Users can track the status of their applications (e.g., applied, interview scheduled). 7. Notifications and Alerts Description: Users receive alerts and notifications about new job postings. Actions: Email Alerts: Users can opt-in for weekly job alerts based on their preferences. In-App Notifications: Real-time notifications for job matches, application status updates, and reminders to complete their profile. 8. User Dashboard and Analytics Description: Users can access analytics about their job search progress. Features: Application History: Overview of all submitted applications and their statuses. Profile Strength Indicator: Visual representation of how complete their profile is and suggestions for improvement. Skill Gap Analysis: Insights into skills they may need to develop for desired roles. 9. Help and Support Description: Assistance for users who need help navigating the site or have questions. Actions: FAQs Section: Common questions and answers about the platform. Contact Support: A form for users to submit inquiries or feedback. 10. Logout Description: Securely log out of the account. Actions: Logout Button: Clearly accessible option to end the session. Oly bhuvaneshwer will come ig Ask him to meet me tmr at lunch ad astra tommorow Jaijan? yes Send his no.
